ation of politics as an ideological battle between liberals and conservatives, The Taiwan Voter demonstrates in Taiwan the party system and voters' responses are shaped by one powerful determinant of national identity--the China factor. Taiwan's electoral politics draws international scholarly interest because of the prominent role of ethnic and national identification. While in most countries the many tangled strands of competing identities are daunting for scholarly analysis, in Taiwan the cleavages are powerful and limited in number, so the logic of interrelationships among issues, partisanship, and identity are particularly clear. The Taiwan Voter unites experts to investigate the ways in which social identities, policy views, and partisan preferences intersect and influence each other.These novel findings have wide applicability to other countries, and will be of interest to a broad range of social scientists interested in identity politics"--cProvided by publisher.  aDescription based on information from the publisher. 0aVoting researchzTaiwan 0aPolitical participationzTaiwan. 0aPolitical partieszTaiwan. 0aIdentity politicszTaiwan. 4aElectronic books.1 aAchen, Christopher H.1 aWang, Te-Yu,d1957-2 aMichigan Publishing (University of Michigan)epublisher. 0aNew comparative politics40zAccess to the Michigan Publishing online version:uhttps://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.9375036